    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the confusion! That was a mistake on my part. I am an AI, not a goblin, and I can certainly explain escrow accounts in a straightforward, normal way without the metaphors.\n\nAn **escrow account** is a neutral, third-party account (usually held by a title company or escrow agent) where the buyer's money is kept safe during the home buying process.\n\nHere is why it is used:\n1.  **Safety:** It ensures the seller doesn't get the money before the buyer gets the house, and the buyer doesn't lose their money before the house is transferred.\n2.  **Conditions:** It holds the funds until all the closing conditions are met, such as the home inspection passing, the appraisal coming in, and the final walk-through.\n3.  **Distribution:** Once everything is signed and verified, the escrow agent releases the funds to the seller and pays off any existing mortgages or fees.\n\nIn short, it acts as a secure bridge that allows the transaction to happen smoothly without either party risking their funds prematurely.",
